Suppose you are the driver of a trolley car hurtling down the track at sixty miles an hour. Up ahead you
see five workers standing on the track, tools in hand. You try to stop, but you can’t. The brakes don’t
work. You feel desperate, because you know that if you crash into these five workers, they will all die.
(Let’s assume you know that for sure.)
Suddenly, you notice a side track, off to the right. There is a worker on that track, too, but only one.
You realize that you can turn the trolley car onto the side track, killing the one worker, but sparing the
five

SOURCE: Sandel, Justice (the original trolley dilemma is by Philippa Foot)
